label: ChronometricDate
definition: The age of a specimen or related materials that is generated from a dating assay.

label: chronometricDateID
definition: An identifier for the set of information associated with a chronometricDate. May be a global unique identifier or an identifier specific to the data set.

label: reportedAge
definition: The unconverted output of a dating protocol. For example, the conventional radiocarbon age.

label: reportedAgeConversionProtocol
definition: The method used for converting the reportedAge into a chronometric date, as captured in the maximumAge, maximumAgeReferenceSystem, minimumAge, and minimumAgeReferenceSystem fields. For example, calibration of conventional radiocarbon age.

label: maximumAge
definition: Upper limit for the age of a specimen as determined by a dating method.

label: maximumAgeReferenceSystem
definition: The reference system associated with the maximumAge. For example, BC.

label: minimumAge
definition: Lower limit for the age of a specimen as determined by a dating method.

label: minimumAgeReferenceSystem
definition: The reference system associated with the minimumAge. For example, AD.

label: ageUncertaintyInYears
definition: The temporal uncertainty of the maximumAge and minimumAge, in years.

label: ageUncertaintyMethod
definition: The method used to generate reported uncertainty calculations.

label: materialDated
definition: A description of the material on which the chronometricDateProtocol was actually performed.

label: materialDatedID
definition: An identifier for the material on which the dating protocol was performed.

label: chronometricDateProtocol
definition: A description or reference to the methods used to determine the chronometricDate.

label: chronometricDateReferences
definition: A list (concatenated and separated) of identifiers (publication, bibliographic reference, global unique identifier, URI) of literature associated with the chronometricDate.

label: chronometricDateRemarks
definition: Notes or comments about the chronometricDate.
